{
  "info": {
    "name": "LearnMap.app API",
    "_postman_id": "b6f6a5b0-1c2a-4b7e-9f3d-1e2a3b4c5d6e",
    "description": "Manual test collection for the LearnMap.app backend (Milestone 1: auth, learning items, study sessions, dashboard/stats).\n\nHow to use:\n1. Make sure the backend is running (locally: `go run ./cmd/server` or the golang:latest container, per docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) and Postgres is up (`docker compose up -d postgres`).\n2. Set the `invite_code` collection variable to match whatever `INVITE_CODE` your running backend was started with.\n3. Run folders top-to-bottom, or use Collection Runner to run the whole collection in one pass — it's designed to be safely re-runnable (Register requests generate a unique email each run).\n4. Requests are grouped so state flows automatically: Register/Login capture `access_token_*` and `user_id_*` into collection variables; Create Item/Session capture their ids. You should not need to copy/paste anything manually.\n\nNotes on refresh-token cookies: Postman's cookie jar is shared per host, not per logical user, so once Bob is registered (near the end, for the cross-user isolation checks) his Set-Cookie response overwrites whatever refresh cookie was stored for Alice. That's why Alice's own Refresh/Logout checks run early, right after she registers, before Bob exists — everything after that only depends on the Bearer access token header, not the cookie, so it isn't affected.\n\nThe single most important thing this collection verifies is in the \"Cross-User Isolation\" folder: Bob, authenticated as himself, attempting to read/rename/complete/delete Alice's learning item and delete her study session — every one of those must come back 404, never the data, and never a distinguishing 403.",
    "schema": "https://schema.getpostman.com/json/collection/v2.1.0/collection.json"
  },
  "auth": {
    "type": "bearer",
    "bearer": [{ "key": "token", "value": "{{access_token_alice}}", "type": "string" }]
  },
  "variable": [
